text: pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology Dutomycin Induces Autophagy and Apoptosis by Targeting the Serine Protease Inhibitor SERPINB6 Mina Jang, Shuta Hara, Gun-Hee Kim, Seung Min Kim, Sangkeun Son, Mincheol Kwon, In-Ja Ryoo, Hyemin Seo, Min Jung Kim, Nam-Doo Kim, Nak-Kyun Soung, Yong Tae Kwon, Bo Yeon Kim, Hiroyuki Osada, Jae-Hyuk Jang,* Sung-Kyun Ko,* and Jong Seog Ahn* ABSTRACT: Autophagy plays an important role in maintaining tumor cell progression and survival in response to metabolic stress. Thus, the regulation of autophagy can be used as a strategy for anticancer therapy. Here, we report dutomycin (DTM) as a novel autophagy enhancer that eventually induces apoptosis due to excessive autophagy. Also, human serine protease inhibitor B6 (SERPINB6) was identiﬁed as a target protein of DTM, and its novel function which is involved in autophagy was studied for the ﬁrst time. We show that DTM directly binds SERPINB6 and then activates intracellular serine proteases, resulting in autophagy induction. Inhibitory eﬀects of DTM on the function of SERPINB6 were conﬁrmed through enzyme- and cell-based approaches, and SERPINB6 was validated as a target protein using siRNA-mediated knockdown and an overexpression test. In a zebraﬁsh xenograft model, DTM showed a signiﬁcant decrease in tumor area. Furthermore, the present ﬁndings will be expected to contribute to the expansion of novel basic knowledge about the correlation of cancer and autophagy by promoting active further research on SERPINB6, which was not previously considered the subject of cancer biology. S erpins (serine protease inhibitors) are members of a

superfamily of proteins that inhibit the activities of target proteases irreversibly by mediating a conformational change.1 Most serpins mainly target extracellular chymotrypsin-like serine proteases to regulate proteolytic cascades, such as coagulation pathways, immune responses, and tissue remodel- ing.2,3 Unlike extracellular serpin clades, intracellular serpins within clade B are predominantly found within the cytoplasm of various cancer cell lines. In humans, deﬁciency or abnormal accumulation of serpins results in several types of disorders named “serpinopathies.”4 Human clade B serpins have been reported to play a cytoprotective and defensive role against injury caused by the inappropriate activity of lysosomal proteases and promote metastatic cancer cell survival.5−7 Human serine protease inhibitor, clade B, member 6 (SERPINB6), thrombin inhibitor generally expressed in endothelial cells, epithelial cells, monocytes, and neutrophils to avoid cellular damage caused by protease leakage from lysosomes.8−10 Previous studies have shown that intracellular SERPINB6 inhibits several serine proteases, such as cathepsin G (CTSG), β-tryptase, kallikrein-2, kallikrein-8, and thrombin, by forming an SDS-stable complex.8−12 In addition, pathology results showed that the homozygous truncating mutation of SERPINB6 was associated with autosomal recessive nonsyndromic sensorineural hearing loss in humans.13 Cite This: ACS Chem. Macroautophagy (hereafter autophagy) is an evolutionarily conserved cellular mechanism that eliminates long-lived proteins and damaged organelles by using lysosomal hydro- lases, playing an essential role in cellular survival, development, and homeostasis.14,15 This intracellular degradative system is triggered by nutrient starvation and degrades unneeded proteins into amino acids for the synthesis of proteins that are crucial for survival.16 Autophagy cargo undergoes several including sequestration by autophagic sequential membranes, called autophagosomes, transport to lysosomes, degradation by lysosomal hydrolases, and utilization of degradation products.17 The lysosome-mediated degradation system not only plays a regulatory role in maintaining cellular homeostasis and survival functions but also has a defensive role against diseases such as microbe infections, aging, neuro- degenerative disorders, and cancer.18 Cancer is one area in which autophagy modulation shows promise as a therapeutic strategy. Here, we screened in-house natural small molecules to ﬁnd novel autophagy regulators, using human cervical carcinoma HeLa cells stably expressing mRFP-EGFP-microtubule-asso- ciated proteins 1A/1B light chain 3B (LC3B). This screening system led to the identiﬁcation of dutomycin (DTM), a tetracyclic quinone glycoside isolated from Streptomyces species.22 Though natural products that share a comparable two examples, chemical backbone with DTM are rare, polyketomycin and cervimycins, exist.23,24 This family of compounds has previously been reported to show strong antibacterial activity and cytotoxicity against several cancer cell lines.22,25 However, the mode of action or other biological activities of these compounds are unknown. In this study, we identiﬁed DTM as a novel autophagy enhancer, and this compound induced not only autophagy but also apoptosis. Screening of potential targets using cellular thermal shift assay (CETSA) and drug aﬃnity responsive the discovery of small molecules that pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology target stability (DARTS) techniques revealed that DTM binds and inhibits SERPINB6.26,27 A direct interaction between SERPINB6 and DTM was conﬁrmed by surface plasmon resonance (SPR) binding analysis and enzymatic assay. We also showed that SERPINB6 is responsible for the biological eﬀects of DTM that we previously observed in cancer cells. Our results explain the anticancer activity of DTM in the zebraﬁsh human cancer xenograft model.

A Cell-Based Screening of an In-House Natural Product Library Identiﬁes DTM As a Novel Autophagy Regulator. To identify autophagy modulators using a cell- based screening system, HeLa cells stably expressing mRFP- EGFP-LC3B were generated.28 A cellomics bioimaging instrument was used to screen an in-house natural small molecule library consisting of 1200 pure compounds obtained from microbes and plants. Sixty-three candidates were selected in the ﬁrst screening, and ﬁve hit compounds were identiﬁed in the second screening using a cellomics bioimaging instrument. Dutomycin (DTM) with the highest activity was then selected as a ﬁnal hit compound which was previously discovered as an antibiotic (Figures 1A and S1−S7). As shown in Figure 1B, DTM exhibited strong cytotoxicity with an approximate IC50 value of 1.4 μM. At a noncytotoxic concentration (0.5−1 μM), DTM strongly induced autophagy as early as 1 h after administration when immunoﬂuorescence staining analyses were performed for EGFP-LC3B, a marker of autophagosomes (Figure 1C,D). This result was validated with immunoblotting analyses of LC3B−II in HeLa cells treated with DTM (Figure 1E), which revealed a dose-responsive accumulation of LC3B−II protein. Interestingly, the levels of LC3B−II increased for 3 h before gradually decreasing in a time-dependent manner (Figure 1F). Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) was used to observe ultrastructural morphological changes, such as cytoplasmic vacuolization, which marks phagophores, autophagosomes, and autolysosomes in a sequential order.29 DTM treatment clearly stimulated the formation of cup-shaped isolation membranes in the cytoplasm which represent phagophores (white arrows), as well as visible double-membraned structures, representing autophagosome (black arrows; Figure 1G). pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology

In addition, because doxorubicin is well-known as a DNA topoisomerase II inhibitor, a human DNA topoisomerase II assay was performed to compare these compounds (Figure S8D).33 According to the results of these assays, both DTM and polyketomycin, the tetracyclic quinone glycosides, and doxorubicin, the anthracycline, might function through distinct cellular mechanisms. DTM Induces Autophagic Flux. An increased level of LC3B−II may be due to autophagy induction or blockage in autophago-lysosomal maturations.29 To assess the impact of DTM on autophagic ﬂux, we performed an LC3B turnover assay to determine degradation of LC3B−II in autolysosomes using Western blot analysis. HeLa cells were treated with DTM in the presence or absence of hydroxychloroquine (HCQ), an autophagy inhibitor that accumulates within lysosomes, resulting in lysosome neutralization and the inhibition of the autophagosome-lysosome fusion step.34 As shown in Figure 2A, cells cotreated with DTM and HCQ had greater amounts of LC3B−II accumulation compared to cells treated with DTM or HCQ alone, indicating that DTM induces autophagic ﬂux. To obtain more direct evidence that DTM enhances autophagic ﬂux, the level of SQSTM1/p62, an in vivo substrate of autophagic degradation, was measured using Western blot analysis. Consistent with LC3B−II results, we observed increased accumulation of SQSTM1/p62 in cells cotreated with DTM and HCQ, as compared with DTM or HCQ alone. Torin 1, a selective ATP-competitive inhibitor of the mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR), exhibited expected eﬃcacy as a positive control. As an alternative method to measure autophagic ﬂux, we monitored lysosomal quenching of EGFP ﬂuorescence of mRFP-EGFP-labeled LC3B under an acidic environment. In contrast to EGFP, mRFP remains stable under low pH conditions. On the basis of this principle, autophagosomes and autolysosomes were marked with yellow and red ﬂuorescence, respectively.35 We observed that cells treated with DTM were enriched for red-colored autolyso- somes, indicative of enhanced autophagic ﬂux (Figure 2B). DTM were enriched for red-colored autolyso- somes, indicative of enhanced autophagic ﬂux (Figure 2B). To obtain additional evidence of autophagy, we also performed immunocytochemisty analysis to observe the colocalization of EGFP-LC3B and lysosomal-associated membrane protein (LAMP)-1, markers for autophagosomes and lysosomes, respectively. Upon DTM treatment, EGFP-LC3B puncta were induced and clearly colocalized with LAMP-1, in contrast to cells treated with HCQ (Figure 2C). Next, we evaluated the lysosomal activity of cells treated with DTM using a red BODIPY dye conjugated to bovine serum albumin, DQ-Red BSA.36 This ﬂuorogenic substrate of proteases is self-quenched under normal conditions but is dequenched and generates a red ﬂuorescence product when cleaved under acidic conditions in lysosomes. As expected, dequenched DQ-Red BSA products were abundantly generated in cells treated with DTM, indicative of a strong lysosomal activity (Figure 2D). Furthermore, we conﬁrmed the induced colocalization of EGFP-LC3B and DQ-Red BSA ﬂuorescence as markers for autophagosomes and lysosomes, respectively. In contrast, red ﬂuorescence was not observed when cells were treated with HCQ.

mTOR is a key regulator of autophagy, whose inhibition induces autophagic ﬂux under nutritional insuﬃciency.37 We therefore examined whether DTM is an mTOR-dependent or -independent autophagy enhancer using Western blot anal- ysis.38 Short-term (0.5 h) exposure of cells to DTM eﬀectively pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology inhibited mTOR phosphorylation and increased expression levels of LC3B−II. In addition, p70S6 kinase (p70S6K), a downstream target of the mTOR pathway, was also involved in DTM-induced autophagy. After a 3 h incubation with DTM, assayed protein levels showed a return (back) to initial levels (Figure 2E). By monitoring the time-course kinetics of mTOR/p70S6K signaling, we concluded that DTM initially induces autophagy via mTOR inhibition, which is followed by down-regulation of autophagy. To further clarify the role of DTM as an autophagy enhancer, we also monitored autophagosome biogenesis through the use of double-FYVE-containing protein 1 (DFCP1) as a marker of preautophagosomal structures, including omegasomes and phagophore-nucleation sites. DTM-treated HeLa cells transiently expressing pMXs-puro GFP-DFCP1 showed increased small cup-shaped ﬂuorescent membrane precursors in a pattern similar to that seen for Torin 1, a positive control (Figure S9). Our results suggest that DTM induces autophagy by inhibiting the mTOR/p70S6K pathway, and thus promoting the formation of autophagosomal structures. DTM Induces Caspase-Dependent Apoptosis. that the active cleavage form of cysteine-aspartic protease (caspase)-9 required for apoptosis was readily generated in cells treated with DTM. As an alternative method to detect apoptosis, we also performed ﬂow cytometry analysis of DTM- treated HeLa cells, using ﬂuorescein isothiocyanate (FITC)- conjugated Annexin-V, which marks phosphatidylserine on the outer membrane of apoptotic cells.39 As shown in Figure 3C, DTM treatment potently induced apoptosis. Next, to conﬁrm whether DTM cytotoxicity is related to autophagic cell death or apoptosis, cells were pretreated with 3-methyladenine (3- MA), wortmannin (phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) inhib- itors), or Z-VAD-ﬂuoromethyl ketone (FMK) (a pan-caspase inhibitor), and then incubated with DTM for 3 or 24 h, respectively (Figure S10A,B). Cells cotreated with DTM and each of the PI3K inhibitors or Z-VAD-FMK showed relatively higher viability than those treated with DTM alone. This result suggests that DTM ﬁnally induces both autophagic cell death and apoptosis in HeLa cells. Autophagy is known to prevent apoptosis induction, while apoptosis-associated caspase activation blocks the process of autophagy.40,41 Thus, we examined cross-talk between autophagy and apoptosis through the inhibition of apoptosis with Z-VAD-FMK.42 When HeLa cells were treated with DTM for the indicated times in the presence or absence of Z-VAD- FMK, we found that LC3B−II levels were retained in cells treated with DTM and Z-VAD-FMK, as compared to DTM alone (Figure S10C). We conﬁrmed that DTM induces autophagic activity prior to apoptosis. The transition from pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology autophagy to apoptosis may be a defense mechanism which is triggered when cells cannot endure stresses.41

Identiﬁcation of SERPINB6 As a Target of DTM. To identify the interactive target protein of DTM, CETSA, and DARTS techniques which rely on measurements of protein thermal stability and limited digestion of protease were performed.43,44 CETSA and DARTS are appropriate methods for validating bioactive compounds which are unamenable to modiﬁcation or conjugation that is required for aﬃnity-based target identiﬁcation. In this study, two techniques that did not require chemical modiﬁcations were combined and used for target identiﬁcation of DTM. As shown in Figure 4A, two visible protein bands with sizes of 37 kDa (a) and 43 kDa (b) were identiﬁed as a cytoplasmic antiproteinase and a thrombin inhibitor, respectively, indicating SERPINB6 as a likely target (Table S1). Most of the serpins are able to be cleaved by nonspeciﬁc serine proteases at the reactive center loop (RCL), which leads to producing a lower molecular weight form of the protein (a).45 To determine whether SERPINB6 is a target of DTM, we performed CETSA and DARTS techniques based on DTM- increased thermal stabilization and resistance to proteolysis. Immunoblot analyses showed that SERPINB6 was signiﬁcantly indicating that DTM stabilized by incubation with DTM, directly binds SERPINB6 (Figure 4B). To examine DTM- target binding, human recombinant SERPINB6 was puriﬁed and veriﬁed the state of human recombinant SERPINB6 using gel permeation chromatography (GPC) for the analysis of polymers (Figure S11A,B). These puriﬁed proteins were expected to be a monomer of SERPINB6 (P2) and misfolded SERPINB6 (P1), through validation of protein native states using electrophoresis (Figure S11C). The proteins in P2 were used in subsequent experiments. As direct evidence, surface plasmon resonance (SPR) analysis was performed for determination of the binding constant using recombinant human SERPINB6. As shown in the sensorgrams (Figure 4C), an association rate (ka) of 831.5 M−1 s−1 and a dissociation rate (kd) of 1.029 × 10−3 s−1 were obtained. The actual binding equilibrium constant (KD) of 1.236 μM was calculated as the ratio of the binding rates (KD = kd/ka). These results conﬁrmed SERPINB6 as a direct target protein of DTM, using SPR analysis. Inhibitory Eﬀects of DTM on the Function of SERPINB6. In general, serpins form complexes with target serine proteases as pseudosubstrates to disrupt their active site by causing proteases to cleave their own peptide bonds in the RCL, which is crucial for serine proteases.8,46 Inhibitory eﬀect of DTM on interaction between SERPINB6 and its partner serine protease, cathepsin G (CTSG), was analyzed using SDS- PAGE. The decreased intact SERPINB6 was observed and accompanied by the lower molecular weight band, which might be the cleaved form in the RCL of SERPINB6 by CTSG, whereas the level of intact SERPINB6 visibly increased in a DTM dose-dependent manner (Figure 4D). In addition, a complex form of SERPINB6 and CTSG was investigated by SDS-PAGE with silver staining, but the protein complex was not detectable at the optimal temperature for enzyme activity (Figure S11D). We also analyzed the interactions between SERPINB6 and several serine proteases, which are known to exist primarily in cancer cells to identify the causative proteases pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology

involved in the activity of DTM (Figure S12). Unfortunately, we could not ﬁnd the serine proteases which interact with SERPINB6. Next, the enzyme activity of CTSG in a mixture of SERPINB6 was measured in the presence or absence of DTM. CTSG enzyme activity was increased as a result of SERPINB6 activity suppression by DTM (Figure 4E). Even though SERPINB6 is also expressed in several human cancer cell lines, CTSG was well-known as a serine protease mainly presenting in azurophilic granules of neutrophilic polymorphonuclear leukocytes.8 Because the serine protease which is involved in the biological activity of DTM has not been determined, the activity of general serine proteases was measured in DTM-treated live cells. FLISP inhibitors used to the intracellular chymotrypsin-like serine protease detect activity were labeled with a red sulforhodamine 101 (SR101) ﬂuorochrome. These inhibitors contain a chloromethyl ketone (CMK) reactive group that can irreversibly bind to the histidine residue in the active site of serine proteases. HeLa cells treated with DTM had notably increased ﬂuorescence, indicating intracellular serine protease activity, in a concen- tration-dependent manner (Figure 5A). To elucidate the correlation of the DTM-induced increase in intracellular serine proteases with autophagy and apoptosis, we investigated the eﬀect of cotreatment with protease inhibitor cocktails and DTM on cancer cells. As seen from the immunoblot results, LC3B−II levels markedly decreased in the cotreated cells as compared to cells treated with DTM alone (Figure 5B). The cytotoxic eﬀects of DTM also diminished with cotreatment with protease inhibitor cocktails (Figure 5C). We also investigated whether an increase in serine protease activity is suﬃcient to induce autophagy. The serine protease inhibitor Pefabloc signiﬁcantly blocked the eﬀect of DTM on the mTOR pathway and thus inhibited the conversion of LC3B−I to LC3B−II (Figure 5E). These data collectively suggest that DTM binds SERPINB6, releasing intracellular serine proteases and leading to autophagic induction. Target Validation of SERPINB6 As a Target of DTM. We examined the impact of SERPINB6 dysregulation associated with autophagic and apoptotic induction. Knock- down of SERPINB6 acutely increased the level of endogenous LC3B−II as well as EGFP-LC3B puncta (Figure 6A,B), leading to gradually reduced cell proliferation in a dose- dependent manner (Figure 6C). To conﬁrm the more certain relationship between SERPINB6 and activities, we generated a CRISPR/Cas9-mediated SERPINB6 knockout HeLa cell line. Knockout of SERPINB6 in cells resulted in an increase of LC3B−II levels, whereas SERPINB6 depletion did not show strong eﬀects on capase-9 activation and cytotoxicity, indicative of apoptosis (Figure S13A,C) compared to DTM pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology treatment. This diﬀerence in cellular eﬀects between gene depletion and chemical treatment might be because several serpins have been reported to simultaneously modulate serine proteases.2,5 In addition, we conﬁrmed that SERPINB6 expression rescued the autophagy induction and the cell growth inhibition caused by SERPINB6 depletion (Figure S13B,C).

To further validate the role of SERPINB6 in DTM-induced biological activities, HeLa cells were transfected with a plasmid encoding SERPINB6-GFP, or a control vector. Overexpression of SERPINB6 signiﬁcantly reduced DTM-induced autophagy, cell death, and caspase-9 activation (Figures 6D,E, and S13D), and intracellular serine protease activity was also diminished in SERPINB6-overexpressed cells by DTM, compared to control vector-transfected cells (Figure 6F). These results provide the evidence for SERPINB6 as the target protein of DTM. DTM Inhibits Human Cancer Cell Progression in a Zebraﬁsh Embryo Xenograft Model. were veriﬁed in HCT-15 cells (Figure S14), and the autophagic and antiproliferative eﬀects of DTM on HCT-15 cells were conﬁrmed (Figure 7B,C). CM-DiI-labeled HCT-15 cells were grafted into the yolk sac of 2 dpf zebraﬁsh embryos, which were then incubated with DMSO or DTM for 3 days. Injected cancer cells showed stable proliferation without immune rejection at 1 day post injection (dpi; Figure 7D). DTM-treated zebraﬁsh embryos showed a signiﬁcant decrease in tumor area (−40.5% at 4 dpi) as compared to the control group (+75.6% at 4 dpi). These results suggest that DTM exhibited a signiﬁcant anticancer activity without damaging zebraﬁsh embryos. In this study, microorganism-produced natural compound DTM was identiﬁed as a novel direct inhibitor of SERPINB6, which potently induces autophagy and apoptosis via intra- cellular serine protease activation in human cancer cells. Above all, the mode of action of DTM was demonstrated for the ﬁrst time that this compound inhibits SERPINB6 from controlling its target proteases, resulting in the activation of serine proteases. In the time-course kinetics experiments where the eﬀects of DTM were monitored, DTM initially induces autophagy via the inhibition of mTOR phosphorylation due pubs.acs.org/acschemicalbiology to an increase in intracellular serine protease activities, whereas long-term exposure to DTM induces a conversion from autophagy to apoptosis (Figure 7E). Our results reported in this study represent the ﬁrst report on bioactivities of DTM against mammalian cancer cells and the possible role of SERPINB6 in induction of the autophagic process, which can be information for understanding new factors involved in autophagy mechanisms.
